The paper focuses on developing a planning approach for a quadruped robot to traverse rough terrain in the absence of visual feedback, while also being able to leverage visual feedback when available. This involves incorporating reflexes and compensating for external disturbances. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of online state-of-the-art algorithms for acquiring a map of the environment, which suggests that it could also belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The use of heuristic-based planning and the incorporation of reflexes and compensation for disturbances suggest that the paper could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. The paper also involves the estimation of unknown time-varying disturbances, which suggests that it could belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves experiments and demonstrations of the proposed approach, which suggests that it could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
